MsmqMessage<T> Class

In this Article

The MsmqMessage(T) class encapsulates aMessage Queuing (MSMQ) message that is sent and received, over a Message Queuing integration channel, to and from an existing Message Queuing application.

Syntax

Declaration

[System.ServiceModel.MessageContract(IsWrapped=false)]
public sealed class MsmqMessage<T>

Type Parameters

T

Represents the message body.

  • MsmqMessage<T>

Constructors

  • MsmqMessage<T>(T)

    Initializes a new instance of the stem.ServiceModel.MsmqIntegration.MsmqMessage`1 class with the provided message body.

    public MsmqMessage (T body);

    Parameters

    • body
      T

      The message body with which to initialize the new instance of the stem.ServiceModel.MsmqIntegration.MsmqMessage`1 class.

    Exceptions

    • ArgumentNullException

      Message body is null.

    Remarks

    A Message Queuing (MSMQ) message can be constructed with a body of type T.

    Example

                Dim message2 As New MsmqMessage(Of String)(message.Body)

                MsmqMessage<string> message2 = new MsmqMessage<string>(message.Body);

Properties

  • AcknowledgeType

    Gets or sets the AcknowledgeTypes that is associated with this message.

    public Nullable<System.Messaging.AcknowledgeTypes> AcknowledgeType { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<AcknowledgeTypes>

      The AcknowledgeTypes that is associated with this message. May be null.

    Remarks

    This property specifies the type of acknowledgment messages that are requested by the sending application. The application can use this property to request notification of certain events. For example, the application might want to be notified when the message reaches its destination queue, when the message is retrieved, or if the message times out before it reaches its destination queue or is retrieved. For member details, see AcknowledgeTypes.

    Example

                message.AcknowledgeType = AcknowledgeTypes.PositiveArrival

                message.AcknowledgeType = AcknowledgeTypes.PositiveArrival;
  • Acknowledgment

    Gets the Acknowledgment that is associated with this message.

    public Nullable<System.Messaging.Acknowledgment> Acknowledgment { get; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<Acknowledgment>

      The Acknowledgment that is associated with this message. The default value is Acknowledgement.None.

    Remarks

    When you receive a message from an administration queue, you can use this property to verify the status of the original message.

    Example

                If message.Acknowledgment = Acknowledgment.Receive Then
                Console.WriteLine("Message sent with Receive acknowledgment")
            End If

                if (message.Acknowledgment == Acknowledgment.Receive)
                Console.WriteLine("Message sent with Receive acknowledgment");
  • AdministrationQueue

    Gets or sets the Uri of the administration queue that is associated with this message.

    public Uri AdministrationQueue { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Uri

      The Uri of the administration queue that is associated with this message. The default value is null.

    Remarks

    The administration queue that is associated with a message will receive any acknowledgment messages that indicate whether the original message reached its destination queue and whether it has been removed from the queue.

    Example

                message.AdministrationQueue = New Uri(".\private$\MyAdminQueue")

                message.AdministrationQueue = new Uri(".\\private$\\MyAdminQueue");
  • AppSpecific

    Gets or sets an Int32 value that represents any additional application-specific information that is associated with this message.

    public Nullable<int> AppSpecific { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<Int32>

      An Int32 value that represents any additional application-specific information that is associated with this message. The default value is null when accessed by the sending application and 0 when accessed by the receiving application.

    Example

                message.AppSpecific = 5

                message.AppSpecific = 5;
  • ArrivedTime

    Gets or sets a DateTime that indicates when the message arrived in the destination queue.

    public Nullable<DateTime> ArrivedTime { get; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<DateTime>

      A DateTime that indicates when the message arrived in the destination queue.

    Example

                Console.WriteLine("Message arrived at the destination queue at {0}", message.ArrivedTime.ToString())

                Console.WriteLine("Message arrived at the destination queue at {0}", message.ArrivedTime.ToString());
  • Authenticated

    Gets a Boolean value that indicates whether the message is authenticated.

    public Nullable<bool> Authenticated { get; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<Boolean>

      true if the message is authenticated; otherwise, false.

    Remarks

    A message is authenticated when the sender requests authentication or sends the message to a message queue that is configured to require authentication.

    Example

                If message.Authenticated = True Then
                Console.WriteLine("Message was authenticated")
            End If

                if (message.Authenticated == true)
                Console.WriteLine("Message was authenticated");
  • Body

    Gets or sets the body of the message.

    public T Body { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • T

      The body of the message.

    Exceptions

    • ArgumentNullException

      Message body is null.

    Example

                Dim body = message.Body

                string body = message.Body;
  • BodyType

    Gets or sets an Int32 value that indicates the type of the body of the message.

    public Nullable<int> BodyType { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<Int32>

      An Int32 value that indicates the type of the body of the message. May be null.

    Remarks

    Message Queuing (MSMQ) recognizes the body contents as an object or as a serialized stream. The BodyType property indicates the type of the object within the Body property of the message.

    The ActiveX formatter performs binding between native types and the object in a message body. If you use the ActiveX formatter, the formatter sets the BodyType property for you.

    Example

                message.BodyType = 23

                message.BodyType = 23;
  • CorrelationId

    Gets or sets a String that contains the correlation identifier for this message.

    public string CorrelationId { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • String

      A String that contains the correlation identifier for this message.

    Remarks

    When Message Queuing (MSMQ) generates an acknowledgment or report message, it uses this property to specify the message identifier of the original message. The application that sent the original message, when it receives an acknowledgment or report message, can get this property from the message it receives to verify the message identifier of the original message.

    The application can also use this property to correlate messages for its own purposes.

    Example

                message.CorrelationId = "This message"

                message.CorrelationId = "This message";
  • DestinationQueue

    Gets the Uri of the destination queue for this message.

    public Uri DestinationQueue { get; }

    Property Value

    • Uri

      The Uri of the destination queue for this message.

    Example

                Console.WriteLine("The destination queue is {0}", message.DestinationQueue.ToString())

                Console.WriteLine("The destination queue is {0}", message.DestinationQueue.ToString());
  • Extension

    Gets or sets an array of Byte that contains any additional, application-defined information that is associated with this message.

    public byte[] Extension { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Byte[]

      An array of Byte that contains any additional, application-defined information that is associated with this message.

    Remarks

    Use this property to store additional information, such as a large binary object.

    Example

                Dim buffer() As Byte = {&H10, &H11, &H12, &H14}
            message.Extension = buffer

                byte[] buffer = {0x10, 0x11, 0x12, 0x14};
            message.Extension = buffer;
  • Id

    Gets a String that contains the message identifier for this message.

    public string Id { get; }

    Property Value

    • String

      A String that contains the message identifier for this message.

    Remarks

    This property can only be accessed after the message is sent.

    Message Queuing (MSMQ) generates a message identifier for the message when it is sent. The identifier is composed of 20 bytes and includes two parts: the machine GUID of the sending computer, and a message identifier that is unique on the sending computer. The combination of these two parts forms a message identifier that is unique on the network.

    Message Queuing generates message identifiers for all messages, including acknowledgment and report messages. Message Queuing sends an acknowledgment message in response to the arrival or failure of a message that is sent by an application.

    Example

                Dim MessageId = message.Id

                string MessageId = message.Id;
  • Label

    Gets or sets a String that contains the message label.

    public string Label { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • String

      A String that contains the message label.

    Remarks

    The message label has no intrinsic meaning to Message Queuing (MSMQ). It is used to identify messages in a human-readable way. Your applications are responsible for interpreting message labels. You do not need to make the message label unique.

    You can use the message label for various purposes, such as displaying it or selectively processing messages based on their labels.

    Example

                message.Label = "Message1 Label"

                message.Label = "Message1 Label";
  • MessageType

    Gets the MessageType that is associated with this message.

    public Nullable<System.Messaging.MessageType> MessageType { get; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<MessageType>

      The MessageType that is associated with this message. May be null.

    Remarks

    Message Queuing (MSMQ) sets this property when it sends a message. A message can have one of the following types:

    • MessageType: A message sent by an application.

    • MessageType: A message that Message Queuing generates when an application sends a normal message and requests an acknowledgment. For example, Message Queuing can generate a positive or negative acknowledgment to indicate whether the original message arrived at its destination queue, or whether it was retrieved from the destination queue by the receiving application. Message Queuing returns the appropriate acknowledgment message to the administration queue specified by the sending application.

    • MessageType: Whenever an application sends a message, if the local Queue Manager has a report queue defined, Message Queuing generates a report message and sends it to the report queue. If tracing is enabled, Message Queuing sends a report message to the report queue each time the original message enters or leaves a Message Queuing server.

    Example

                Console.WriteLine("The message type is {0}", message.MessageType)

                Console.WriteLine("The message type is {0}", message.MessageType);
  • Priority

    Gets or sets the MessagePriority that is associated with this message.

    public Nullable<System.Messaging.MessagePriority> Priority { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<MessagePriority>

      The MessagePriority that is associated with this message. May be null.

    Remarks

    The message priority affects how Message Queuing (MSMQ) handles the message both while the message is in transit and when it reaches its destination queue. A message with a higher priority is given preference during routing, and is inserted closer to the front of its destination queue. Messages with the same priority are placed in the destination queue according to their arrival times.

    Example

                message.Priority = MessagePriority.Normal

                message.Priority = MessagePriority.Normal;
  • ResponseQueue

    Gets or sets the Uri of the message queue that receives response messages from the receiving application.

    public Uri ResponseQueue { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Uri

      This property defaults to null.

      This property identifies the queue that receives response messages that the receiving application returns to the sending application. The sending application specifies the response queue when it sends messages to the receiving application. The sending application can specify any available queue as the response queue.

    Example

                message.ResponseQueue = New Uri(".\private$\MyResponseQueue")

                message.ResponseQueue = new Uri(".\\private$\\MyResponseQueue");
  • SenderId

    Gets an array of Byte that contains the sender identifier of the sending application.

    public byte[] SenderId { get; }

    Property Value

    • Byte[]

      An array of Byte that contains the sender identifier of the sending application.

    Remarks

    Message Queuing (MSMQ) attaches the sender identifier of the sending application to the message. This property can be used by the receiving application to perform authorization checks.

    Example

                Console.WriteLine("SenderID is {0}", message.SenderId)

                Console.WriteLine("SenderID is {0}", message.SenderId);
  • SentTime

    Gets a DateTime that indicates when the message was sent by the queue manager of the sending application's computer.

    public Nullable<DateTime> SentTime { get; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<DateTime>

      A DateTime that indicates when the message was sent by the queue manager of the sending application's computer. May be null.

    Remarks

    The sent time is adjusted to the local time of the sending application's computer. The source and destination queues may be on computers with different time zones.

    The default for this property is null.

    Example

                Console.WriteLine("Message was sent at {0}", message.SentTime)

                Console.WriteLine("Message was sent at {0}", message.SentTime);
  • TimeToReachQueue

    Gets or sets a TimeSpan that indicates the maximum amount of time allowed for the message to reach the destination queue.

    public Nullable<TimeSpan> TimeToReachQueue { get; set; }

    Property Value

    • Nullable<TimeSpan>

      A TimeSpan that indicates the maximum amount of time allowed for the message to reach the destination queue. May be null.

    Remarks

    If the interval specified by this property expires before the message reaches its destination queue, Message Queuing (MSMQ) discards the message in one of two ways. If the message's UseDeadLetterQueue property is true, the message is sent to the dead-letter queue. Otherwise, the message is dropped.

    The default for this property is null.

    Example

                message.TimeToReachQueue = New TimeSpan(0, 10, 0)

                message.TimeToReachQueue = new TimeSpan(0,10,0);
